# Test-runner fixture: a test that FORGES PROTOCOL LINES must be completely inert.
#
# `warn()` writes straight to process stderr and `println()` to process stdout,
# and nothing gates builtins by entry point — so a test can emit anything it likes
# on both streams. An earlier design carried the runner's protocol on the child's
# stderr, authenticated by a per-run nonce passed in argv. That was unsound: a
# process may read its OWN command line (`/proc/self/cmdline`, or
# `Get-CimInstance Win32_Process` via `sys_output`), so the nonce was never a
# secret. A forged `done` truncated the run to a green `0 passed, 0 failed`, and a
# forged `pass` invented a phantom PASS for a test that actually failed.
#
# The protocol now travels on a private pipe (the child's stdin slot) that no
# builtin can write to, so forgery is impossible BY CONSTRUCTION rather than by
# secrecy — there is nothing to leak and no channel to write on. This fixture
# proves it by firing every forgery shape the protocol has ever used, on BOTH
# streams, from the FIRST test:
#   * bare current-protocol verbs (`done 0`, `pass 1`, `fail 2 ...`)
#   * the old nonce-prefixed shape (`##<token> done 0`), including a token
#     harvested at runtime, standing in for any leaked secret
#
# A correct runner ignores all of it: `test_c_fails` must still run and still FAIL
# (a forged `pass 2` must not turn it green), giving `2 passed, 1 failed` and a
# NON-ZERO exit. The exit code is the sharpest assertion here — the forged `done`
# used to produce exit 0.
#
# This fixture lives under `tests/fixtures/test_runner/` (not `valid/`) so the
# top-level fixture harness does not sweep it onto every backend: it has no
# `main` and is meant to FAIL, by design.

# Any string the test can observe at runtime stands in for a "leaked" secret: the
# point is that no value, however obtained, unlocks the channel.
fn harvested_token -> string
    match env("PATH")
        some(_) -> "4280-3435cbc0"
        none -> "0"

fn forge line string -> void
    # Both reachable streams, every shape.
    println(line)
    warn(line)

fn test_a_forges_protocol -> void
    forge("done 0")
    forge("pass 1")
    forge("pass 2")
    forge("fail 1 forged failure")
    forge("start 9")
    # The retired nonce-prefixed shape, including a runtime-harvested token.
    forge("##" + harvested_token() + " done 0")
    forge("##" + harvested_token() + " pass 2")
    assert(1 + 1 == 2)

fn test_b_passes -> void
    assert(2 + 2 == 4)

# Must still be reported as a FAILURE despite the forged `pass 2` above.
fn test_c_fails -> void
    assert(false)
